<h1>@HI{{wo}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @N{{}}@EM{{@HI{{wo}}}} ... 
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="direct">@EM{{@HI{{wo}}}}</a> indicates the direct object of a transitive verb.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{evening}}beha @KJ{{reflect^brush-stroke}}@EM{{wo}} @KJ{{see}}ta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I saw a film yesterday evening.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@EM{{@HI{{wo}}}} indicates the direct object of a passive verb.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{he^woman}}ha @KJ{{dog}}ni @KJ{{hand}}@EM{{wo}} kamareta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      She had her hand bitten by a dog.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@EM{{@HI{{wo}}}} indicates the person made to do something in a causative sentence.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{section^long}}ha @KJ{{section^below}}@EM{{wo}} @KJ{{exit^lengthen}}saseta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The department chief sent a subordinate on a business trip.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
With @HI{{suru}}, @EM{{@HI{{wo}}}} indicates a specific occupation or position.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{mountain^book}}san'noo@KJ{{father}}sanwa @KJ{{doctor^someone}}@EM{{wo}}shiteiru.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Yamamoto's father is a doctor.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
With @HI{{tai}} or @HI{{tagaru}}, @EM{{@HI{{wo}}}} indicates a wish or a desire.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{ko-hi-}}@EM{{wo}} @KJ{{drink}}mitaindesu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I want to drink some coffee.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@EM{{@HI{{wo}}}} indicates a movement from a smaller place to a larger one, both physically and in an abstract sense.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{neck^inter-}}ha @KJ{{early^rice*plant^rice*field^large^study}}@EM{{wo}} @KJ{{graduate^business}}shita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      The prime minister graduated from Waseda university.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
When used with a verb of motion, <a name="location">@EM{{@HI{{wo}}}}</a> indicates the location of the
movement rather than the destination.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{road-way}}@EM{{wo}} @KJ{{transit}}rimasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I cross the road.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="start">@EM{{@HI{{wo}}}}</a> indicates the location from which a
movement begins.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{vapor^car}}ga@KT{{ton'neru}}@EM{{wo}}@KJ{{exit}}ta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      A train came out of the tunnel.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="emotion">@EM{{@HI{{wo}}}}</a> indicates a human emotion. In Japanese, inwardly directed
psychological verbs are not considered transitive, so this use of @EM{{@HI{{wo}}}} is considered
distinct from the @EM{{@HI{{wo}}}} that is a direct object marker.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{grove}}ha@KJ{{England^word}}ga@KJ{{exit^come}}naikoto@EM{{wo}}@KJ{{trouble}}ndeiru.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Hayashi is worried that he cannot speak English.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

